## 5. Routing map

All routes live in `src/App.tsx`. Three categories:

### 5.1 Public

| Path | Page | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `/welcome` | `Welcome` | Marketing / landing |
| `/auth` | `Auth` | Email + password login & signup |
| `/staff-login` | `StaffLogin` | QR / phone-only login for field staff |
| `/reset-password` | `ResetPassword` | Password reset |
| `/g/:slug` | `GuestBook` | Guest property page |
| `/s/:slug` | `GuestReservation` | Guest reservation page |
| `/r/:slug` | `ReportIssue` | Guest issue reporting |
| `/v/:orgId` | `Showcase` | Public org showcase |
| `/redeem/:code` | `RedeemCoupon` | Coupon redemption |

### 5.2 Authenticated (any logged-in user)

| Path | Page |
|---|---|
| `/` | `Home` (dispatches based on role) |
| `/admin/dashboard` | `Home` → `Dashboard` |
| `/cohost/dashboard` | `Home` → `Dashboard` |
| `/employee` | `Home` → `MyAgenda` |
| `/guest`, `/guest-preview/:reservationId` | `GuestPortal` |
| `/properties` | `Properties` |
| `/team`, `/cohosts/:id` | `Team`, `CohostDetail` |
| `/anomalies` | `Anomalies` |
| `/reservations` | `Reservations` |
| `/tasks` | `Tasks` |
| `/inventory` | `Inventory` |
| `/availability` | `Availability` |
| `/rentals` | `Rentals` |
| `/settings` | `Settings` |
| `/guest-books`, `/tickets`, `/showcase` (BookingRequests), `/reports`, `/help` | misc |
| `/invoices` | `MyInvoices` |

### 5.3 Super-admin only

| Path | Page |
|---|---|
| `/super-admin` | `SuperAdmin` (list of organizations) |
| `/super-admin/orgs/:id` | `SuperAdminOrg` |
| `/super-admin/billing` | `SuperAdminBilling` |
| `/super-admin/profiles` | `SuperAdminProfiles` |
| `/super-admin/staff` | `SuperAdminStaff` |

`/super-admin/*` routes are mounted as `ProtectedRoute` only — they rely
on each page running its own `isSuperAdminUser()` check and rendering
`<Unauthorized />` for non-super-admins.

### 5.4 Application modules

The same routes seen through a product lens. Five user-facing modules,
each backed by one or more pages in §5.1-5.3.

1. **Super-Admin Console** (`/super-admin/*`)
   _Audience: Escapar staff (`role = 'super_admin'`)._
   Cross-tenant control plane. Lists every organization (`SuperAdmin`),
   drills into a single org (`SuperAdminOrg`), manages billing
   (`SuperAdminBilling`), inspects every profile across tenants
   (`SuperAdminProfiles`), and reviews staff (`SuperAdminStaff`).
   Backed by `organizations`, `profiles`, `subscriptions`, `invoices`.
   Only role that can satisfy RLS via `is_super_admin()` — bypasses
   `org_id` matching everywhere.
   _Status: mostly working — see §8 for the field-name mismatches in
   `SuperAdmin.tsx`._

2. **Admin Dashboard** (`/admin/dashboard`, `/properties`, `/team`,
   `/reservations`, `/tasks`, `/reports`, `/settings`, …)
   _Audience: org owners (`role = 'admin' | 'co_admin'`)._
   Full management surface scoped to the user's `org_id`. Property
   CRUD, booking management, task assignment, team / cohost
   management, org branding and billing. The same routes are shared
   with cohosts — page-level filtering does the scoping.
   _Status: working for the core CRUD; pages that depend on missing
   tables (Anomalies, Inventory, Tickets, BookingRequests) are
   broken._

3. **Cohost Dashboard** (`/cohost/dashboard` plus the shared admin
   routes)
   _Audience: `role = 'cohost'`, or any user with at least one
   `property_cohosts` row._
   Same UI shell as the admin dashboard, but data is filtered to
   properties the user is assigned to. Permission tokens on
   `property_cohosts.permissions` (`manage_properties`,
   `manage_reservations`, `manage_tasks`, `manage_staff`,
   `view_financials`, `manage_settings`) decide what each cohost can
   do on a given property.
   _Status: scoping works; granular per-permission gating is partial._

4. **Employee Agenda** (`/employee`)
   _Audience: field staff (`cleaner`, `driver`, `decorator`,
   `maintenance`, `staff`)._
   Deliberately simple `MyAgenda` page: big buttons, today/tomorrow
   task list, photo upload, voice recording. Reads `tasks` filtered
   by `assigned_to = auth.uid()`. Login via `/staff-login` supports
   QR-code / phone-only flows.
   _Status: the most stable surface of the app._

5. **Guest Pages** (`/g/:slug`, `/s/:slug`, `/r/:slug`, `/v/:orgId`,
   `/redeem/:code`, plus authenticated `/guest`)
   _Audience: end guests staying at a property. Mostly unauthenticated._
   Property info, reservation details, services / rentals to book,
   coupon redemption, issue reporting, public org showcase.
   _Status: mostly broken — depends on `guest_books`, `guest_albums`,
   `guest_uploads`, `guest_messages`, `reservations`,
   `partner_coupons`, `partner_services` — none of which exist in
   the live DB. Listed in §6.2._

A Marketplace and Partner Portal are planned (see §13) but not
implemented; no routes are reserved for them yet.

---

## 6. Database schema (live deployment)

The source of truth for "what tables actually exist in production" is
`src/integrations/supabase/types.ts` — it is auto-generated from the
running Supabase project.

### 6.1 Tables present

| Table | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `profiles` | Per-user row keyed on `auth.users.id`. Holds `role`, `org_id`, `active`, `email`, `full_name`, `phone`, `whatsapp`, `language`, `avatar_url`. The migration `20260516120000` also adds invitation fields (`pending_org_id`, `pending_role`, `invited_by`, `invitation_status`) — these are referenced by RLS policies but may not yet appear in `types.ts` if it hasn't been regenerated since that migration ran. |
| `organizations` | Tenant root. Branding (`logo_url`, `primary_color`, `secondary_color`, `brand_name`), plan (`plan`, `subscription_status`, `trial_ends_at`, `next_billing_date`), quotas (`max_properties`, `max_employees`), defaults (`default_currency`, `default_language`), `owner_id`, `slug`, `active`. |
| `properties` | Belongs to an org via `org_id`. Address, capacity, pricing fields, channel URLs (`airbnb_url`, `booking_url`, `vrbo_url`, `expedia_url`), `amenities` (JSON), `cover_image_url`, `active`. |
| `property_cohosts` | Many-to-many between `profiles` and `properties`. `permissions text[]` per assignment, plus `assigned_at` / `assigned_by`. |
| `bookings` | Belongs to org + property. Customer fields, `checkin`, `checkout`, `nights`, channel info (`channel_slug`, `channel_ref`), pricing breakdown (`nightly_rate`, `accommodation_total`, `cleaning_fee`, `services_total`, `rental_items_total`, `discount_pct`, `grand_total`), `services JSON`, `rental_items JSON`, `status`, `payment_status`, `payment_method`, `ref_number`, optional `cohost_id`. |
| `booking_channels` | Lookup for booking sources (Airbnb, Booking.com, direct, etc.). `slug`, `name`, `icon`, `color`, `default_commission_pct`, `default_payout_delay_days`, `active`. |
| `tasks` | Belongs to org, optionally to a property and booking. `task_type` (e.g. `cleaning`, `maintenance`), `status`, `priority`, `scheduled_date`, `scheduled_time`, `assigned_to`, `assigned_by`, `completed_at`, `completed_photo_url`, `ref_number`. |
| `services` | Per-org service catalog (welcome basket, transfers, etc.). `category`, `price`, `currency`, `commission_pct`, `duration_hours`, optional external provider. |
| `rental_items` | Per-org rentable items (baby beds, beach packs). `daily_price`, `weekly_price`, `deposit`, `stock_quantity`, `category`, `icon`, `image_url`. |
| `subscriptions` | Billing rows per org. `plan`, `status`, `billing_cycle`, `amount`, `currency`, `stripe_subscription_id`, `starts_at`, `ends_at`. |
| `invoices` | Invoice records. `invoice_number`, `amount`, `currency`, `status`, `due_date`, `paid_at`, `pdf_url`. |
| `audit_log` | Generic event log. `action`, `resource_type`, `resource_id`, `user_id`, `user_name`, `user_role`, `org_id`, `details JSON`. |

Plus two views: `bookings_with_property` and `tasks_with_property` —
denormalised joins used to avoid N+1 in lists.

### 6.2 Tables the code references but the live DB does NOT have

The codebase still calls `.from(…)` on the following tables, but they
are absent from the current `types.ts` (so any such query returns an
error / empty result):

`ad_banners`, `ad_impressions`, `booking_requests`, `cleaning_checklists`,
`coupon_redemptions`, `guest_accounts`, `guest_albums`, `guest_books`,
`guest_messages`, `guest_uploads`, `inventory_items`, `inventory_movements`,
`maintenance_tickets`, `message_templates`, `notifications`,
`partner_coupons`, `partner_services`, `property_approval_events`,
`property_ical_feeds`, `property_members`, `public_properties`,
`reservation_rentals`, `reservations`, `task_photos`, `user_roles`.

This is the single most important thing for a new contributor to
internalise. Migrations from early May created many of these tables and
later migrations dropped them; the UI never caught up. Pages like
`GuestBooks`, `Tickets`, `Inventory`, `Anomalies`, and `BookingRequests`
will throw or render empty until either (a) the matching tables come
back as migrations, or (b) the pages are rewritten/removed.

### 6.3 Migrations

Migrations live in `supabase/migrations/` and follow the standard
Supabase naming (`<UTC-timestamp>_<slug>.sql`). They are applied with
`supabase db push` and tracked in
`supabase_migrations.schema_migrations` on the remote DB. Migrations
should never be edited after they ship — write a new one on top.

A recent cluster worth knowing about:

- `20260514130000_is_super_admin_uses_profiles_role.sql` — moves
  `is_super_admin()` off the legacy `user_roles` table and onto
  `profiles.role`.
- `20260515160000_has_role_uses_profiles_role.sql` — same change for
  the generic `has_role()` function.
- `20260516120000_fix_rls_for_super_admin_inserts.sql` — rewrites RLS
  policies on `tasks` and `properties` to use the actual column name
  `org_id` (older policies wrote `organization_id`, which evaluated
  to NULL).
- `20260516130000_restrict_profiles_visibility.sql` — tightens
  read access on `profiles`.

### 6.4 Row Level Security model

All real tables enable RLS. The recurring pattern (post-2026-05-16) is:

- `is_super_admin(auth.uid())` → unconditional access.
- Otherwise, match `org_id` against the caller's `profiles.org_id` _or_
  `profiles.pending_org_id` for invited-but-not-confirmed users.
- For `properties`, also allow cohosts who appear in
  `property_cohosts` for that property.
- For `tasks`, additionally allow the assignee
  (`assigned_to = auth.uid()`).
- INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE on org-scoped tables additionally require
  `profiles.role IN ('admin', 'co_admin', 'cohost', 'super_admin')`.

`is_super_admin()` now reads from `profiles.role`. The deployment has no
`user_roles` table — references to it in the application code
(`access.ts → isSuperAdminUser`) and in some older migrations are
defensive fallbacks and will silently no-op.

---

## 7. Access control helpers (`src/lib/access.ts`)

Every page that needs role-aware behaviour goes through this module
rather than reading `profiles.role` ad hoc.

```ts
import { getUserAccess } from "@/lib/access";

const access = await getUserAccess(user.id);
// → {
//   orgId, role, dashboardPath,
//   isSuperAdmin, isAdmin, isCohost,
//   isManager  // admin OR cohost (incl. property_cohosts assignment)
//   isStaff    // strictly not a manager
// }
```

Lower-level helpers:

- `isAdminRole(role)`, `isSuperAdminRole(role)`, `isOrgAdminRole(role)`,
  `isEmployeeRole(role)` — predicates over a string role.
- `getDashboardPathForRole(role, hasCohostAssignments)` — used both at
  login dispatch and inside `AppLayout` to compute the dashboard link.
- `isGlobalAdmin(userId)` / `isSuperAdminUser(userId)` — single-call
  checks. `isSuperAdminUser` also queries `user_roles` for back-compat
  (returns false if the table is missing).
- `getPropertyPermissions(userId, propertyId)` — returns the
  `permissions text[]` granted via `property_cohosts`, or the full
  manager permission set for global admins.
- `hasPropertyPermission(userId, propertyId, permission)` — sugar over
  the above.

The currently used permission tokens are:
`manage_properties`, `manage_reservations`, `manage_tasks`,
`manage_staff`, `view_financials`, `manage_settings`.

---

## 8. Page-by-page status

This is the realistic state — what renders today vs what depends on
missing schema.

| Page | Works? | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `Welcome`, `Auth`, `StaffLogin`, `ResetPassword` | yes | Supabase Auth flow is wired and tested. |
| `Home` | yes | Role dispatch routes correctly per `getUserAccess`. |
| `Dashboard` (admin / cohost) | partial | Reads `properties`, `profiles`, `tasks`, `property_cohosts` — all real. Some KPI cards may show 0 if no data exists. |
| `MyAgenda` (employee) | yes | Reads `tasks` filtered by `assigned_to`. The simple, working UI. |
| `Properties` | yes | CRUD against `properties`. |
| `Reservations` | yes | Reads `bookings` (renamed from `reservations`). Some legacy code paths may still reference `reservations` — see §6.2. |
| `Tasks` | yes | CRUD against `tasks`. |
| `Team`, `CohostDetail` | yes | Operates over `profiles` + `property_cohosts`. |
| `Settings` | partial | Org branding works (`organizations`); other tabs may rely on missing tables. |
| `SuperAdmin*` | mostly | The whole `/super-admin/*` cluster works against `organizations`, `profiles`, `subscriptions`, `invoices`. Note: `SuperAdmin.tsx` declares an in-file `Org` type with fields `brand_color`, `max_cohosts`, `suspended` that don't match the live schema (`primary_color`, `max_employees`, `active`) — those bindings will be `undefined` until the page is updated. |
| `GuestBook` (`/g/:slug`) | broken | References `guest_books`, `guest_albums`, `guest_uploads`, `guest_messages`. None exist. |
| `GuestReservation`, `GuestPortal`, `ReportIssue` | broken/partial | Depend on guest tables and `reservations`. |
| `Anomalies`, `Inventory`, `Tickets`, `BookingRequests`, `GuestBooks`, `Rentals`, `Availability` | broken/empty | All reference tables that don't exist in the deployment (`maintenance_tickets`, `inventory_items`, `booking_requests`, `property_ical_feeds`, etc.). |
| `Reports`, `MyInvoices` | partial | Invoices work via `invoices` table; non-invoice reports likely empty. |
| `Showcase` (`/v/:orgId`), `RedeemCoupon` | broken | Depend on missing public/coupon tables. |

The supported "happy path" today is: super-admin manages orgs → admin
manages properties / bookings / tasks → field staff sees `MyAgenda`.
Everything else is partially wired.

---

## 9. Internationalisation

Three languages: French (default), English, Arabic. Switcher in
`LanguageSwitcher.tsx`. `i18next-browser-languagedetector` picks an
initial language; the user's stored `profiles.language` overrides it at
login (see `AppLayout`). RTL is not currently themed beyond the
language switch.

---

## 10. Developer setup

```bash
# 1. Install
npm install              # or bun install — lockfile present for both

# 2. Run
npm run dev              # Vite at http://localhost:8080

# 3. Tests
npm test                 # Vitest unit tests
npm run lint             # ESLint

# 4. E2E (Playwright)
#    Fill in .env first — see §10.1
npx playwright install   # first time only
npx playwright test
```

### 10.1 Environment variables

| Var | Where | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `VITE_DEBUG_AUTH_REDIRECT` | optional | Forces auth-redirect debug logging on. |
| `E2E_BASE_URL` | `.env` | Base URL for Playwright runs. |
| `E2E_{SUPER_ADMIN,ADMIN,COHOST,STAFF}_{EMAIL,PASSWORD}` | `.env` | Per-role logins used by `e2e/login-role-redirect.spec.ts`. |

Supabase URL + anon key are **not** environment variables today —
they're hard-coded in `src/integrations/supabase/client.ts`. If you
move them to env, update both the client file and `types.ts` import.

### 10.2 Working with the database

The Supabase project is named `escapar` (id `pqaxxhateycrklzlnhkc`).
Two common workflows:

1. **Schema change** → write a new migration under `supabase/migrations/`,
   run `supabase db push`. Never edit older files.
2. **Data fix / recovery** → write a script in the project root (see
   `restore_profiles_from_auth.sql` for the pattern). Run it once in the
   SQL Editor. These scripts are idempotent (`ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`,
   `WHERE … IS NULL`).

To regenerate `src/integrations/supabase/types.ts`:
```bash
npx supabase gen types typescript --project-id pqaxxhateycrklzlnhkc > src/integrations/supabase/types.ts
```

---

## 11. Deployment

- **Web**: Vercel, project linked to this repository. `vercel.json`
  rewrites all paths to `/` so client-side routing handles deep links.
  Production URL: `abbiatti-com.vercel.app`. Target domain:
  `escapar.net`.
- **Desktop**: Electron 41 wraps `dist/index.html`. Build with
  `ELECTRON_BUILD=1 npm run build` (so Vite uses relative `base: "./"`),
  then point Electron at `dist/`. Packaging via `@electron/packager`.
- **Database**: Supabase managed Postgres. Migrations push via
  Supabase CLI.

---

## 12. Conventions and rules

These come from `CLAUDE.md` and are enforced in code review:

- **Read `profiles.role` from the database, never from client state.**
  All role decisions go through `getUserAccess` / `isSuperAdminUser`.
- **Wrap every authenticated page in `ProtectedRoute`.** Then do the
  role-specific gating inside the page or layout.
- **Don't instantiate new Supabase clients.** Always import from
  `@/integrations/supabase/client`.
- **Employee UI stays simple.** `MyAgenda` is the model: big buttons,
  photo upload, voice recording, no dense tables.
- **Allowed table set**: `profiles`, `properties`, `tasks`, `bookings`,
  `property_cohosts`, `organizations`, `services` (plus the ones
  documented in §6.1). Do not invent tables. If a feature needs a new
  table, write a migration first.
- **Marketplace and WhatsApp Cloud API are not implemented.** Stub them
  out or omit — do not fake successful network calls.

---

## 13. Roadmap (planned, not implemented)

From `README.md`, in rough priority order:

1. Rebuild the broken pages in §8 by either restoring their tables in
   migrations or rewriting them against the current schema.
2. Complete the guest portal (`/g/:slug`): services booking, photo
   uploads with watermark, coupons, WhatsApp messaging.
3. Marketplace: hosts renting items to other hosts, 10% Escapar
   commission, driver-based delivery.
4. Review system (guest → property, cohost → employee).
5. WhatsApp Cloud API integration: welcome, reminders, checkout
   messages.
6. Cut domain over to `escapar.net`, security audit, performance pass.

